<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="516" pageId="1" pageNumber="512" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1665,2016]" box="[199,564,1809,1836]" pageId="1" pageNumber="512">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,564,1809,1836]" pageId="1" pageNumber="512">
Description of 
<typeStatus box="[375,478,1810,1836]" pageId="1" pageNumber="512">holotype</typeStatus>
female
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1665,2016]" lastBlockId="5.[151,1437,152,791]" lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="516" pageId="1" pageNumber="512">
Specimen complete. Body ferruginous; with about 25 long, broad lateral wax pencils extending radially around entire margin, appearing to have 12 lateral pairs and one arising from posterior apex of body; base of each pencil supported by 2 or 3 long flagellate setae (
<figureCitation box="[642,753,1917,1943]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 1" captionStart-1="FIGURE 2" captionStart-2="FIGURE 3" captionStartId-0="2.[151,250,1933,1958]" captionStartId-1="3.[151,250,1916,1941]" captionStartId-2="4.[151,250,971,996]" captionTargetBox-0="[156,1431,181,1906]" captionTargetBox-1="[153,1435,181,1891]" captionTargetBox-2="[188,1399,181,945]" captionTargetId-0="figure@2.[156,1431,181,1906]" captionTargetId-1="figure@3.[153,1435,181,1891]" captionTargetId-2="figure@4.[188,1399,181,945]" captionTargetPageId-0="2" captionTargetPageId-1="3" captionTargetPageId-2="4" captionText-0="FIGURE 1. Dorsal view of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber. Scale bar = 1.0 mm." captionText-1="FIGURE 2. Ventral view of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber. B= rostrum. O = ovisac. Scale bar = 0.2 mm." captionText-2="FIGURE 3. Lateral view of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber. Scale bar = 1.0 mm." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943991" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943993" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943995" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3943991/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3943993/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/3943995/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="512">Figs. 1–3</figureCitation>
). Dorsal and ventral surfaces apparently lacking large wax structures; wax-producing pores and ducts indiscernible. Body length, including wax pencils, 4.0 mm; body length without pencils, 
<quantity box="[339,428,1989,2016]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="1" pageNumber="512" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
; body width including wax pencils 
<quantity box="[831,921,1989,2016]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="1" pageNumber="512" unit="mm" value="3.3">3.3 mm</quantity>
; body width without pencils, 
<quantity box="[1256,1346,1989,2016]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="512" unit="mm" value="0.8">0.8 mm</quantity>
. Length of individual wax pencils, 
<quantity box="[445,582,152,179]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="0.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.8" valueMin="0.5">0.5‒1.8 mm</quantity>
. Antenna appears to be 7-segmented; segment I 
<quantity box="[1115,1201,152,179]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="175.0">175 µm</quantity>
long, segment II 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.59" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="159.0">159 µm</quantity>
, segment III 
<quantity box="[340,429,189,215]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.69" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="169.0">169 µm</quantity>
, segment IV 
<quantity box="[579,668,188,215]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="175.0">175 µm</quantity>
, segment V 
<quantity box="[808,897,188,215]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.59" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="159.0">159 µm</quantity>
, segment VI 
<quantity box="[1047,1136,188,215]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="175.0">175 µm</quantity>
, and terminal segment VII 
<quantity box="[151,238,225,251]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.84" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="284.0">284 µm</quantity>
long, overall length 
<quantity box="[472,561,225,251]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
; each segment with numerous stout flagellate setae; unusual sensilla or empty setal collars present near base of segment VII at juncture with VI, with dual sockets (
<figureCitation box="[1103,1173,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1975,2000]" captionTargetBox="[188,1399,1018,1949]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[188,1399,1018,1949]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Detail of terminal antennomere of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber; image and illustration of claw. Arrow shows constricted “knob” at tip. Scale bar = 57 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943997" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943997/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="516">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
); distal half of terminal antennomere swollen, with slight constriction near apex forming knob-like tip 
<quantity box="[1049,1123,297,323]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="23.0">23 µm</quantity>
long; apex of antennomere with lanceolate terminal spine 
<quantity box="[491,563,333,359]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="22.0">22 µm</quantity>
long and 3 or 4 falcate sensory setae (
<figureCitation box="[982,1058,333,359]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1975,2000]" captionTargetBox="[188,1399,1018,1949]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[188,1399,1018,1949]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Detail of terminal antennomere of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber; image and illustration of claw. Arrow shows constricted “knob” at tip. Scale bar = 57 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943997" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943997/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="516">Figs. 4</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[1111,1127,332,359]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="5.[151,250,1919,1944]" captionTargetBox="[170,1418,813,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[170,1418,813,1894]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURE 5. Protarsus (T) and terminal antennomere (A) of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber. Scale bar = 235 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943999" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943999/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="516">5</figureCitation>
). Legs long, each sub-equal in length to body; each leg segment distinct, without fusion between trochanter and femur or between tibia and tarsus; hind femur 
<quantity box="[334,422,405,431]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.409999999999999" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="641.0">641 µm</quantity>
long, hind tibia 
<quantity box="[608,696,405,431]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.7" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="770.0">770 µm</quantity>
long, hind tarsus 
<quantity box="[898,986,405,431]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.46" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="346.0">346 µm</quantity>
long (
<figureCitation box="[1059,1127,405,431]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="4.[151,250,971,996]" captionTargetBox="[188,1399,181,945]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[188,1399,181,945]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 3. Lateral view of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber. Scale bar = 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3943995" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3943995/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="516">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
); tibial and tarsal segments each with numerous stout flagellate setae; each tarsus slender and articulated at base, bearing a single claw with bifid tip and well-developed plantar denticle near middle; hind claw 
<quantity box="[906,978,476,503]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="95.0">95 µm</quantity>
long; with single pointed digitule present at inner base of claw, 
<quantity box="[389,460,513,539]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.6" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="26.0">26 µm</quantity>
long (
<figureCitation box="[530,597,513,540]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1381,1406]" captionTargetBox="[354,1234,181,1356]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[354,1234,181,1356]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 6. Tarsus with single claw of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber; image and illustration. Scale bar = 84 µm. Insert shows detail of bifid claw. Arrowhead shows digitule. Arrow shows denticle. Scale bar = 32 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3944001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3944001/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="516">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
); trochanteral pores indiscernible. Eyes round, black, protruding from head, detached from base of antenna, each about 
<quantity box="[634,707,548,575]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.8" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="58.0">58 µm</quantity>
in diameter (
<figureCitation box="[855,924,549,575]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1979,2004]" captionTargetBox="[217,1371,1464,1954]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[217,1371,1464,1954]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 7. Eyes of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber; image and illustration of eye. Scale bar = 22 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3944003" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3944003/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="516">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Rostrum 3-segmented, conical to triangular, arising between forelegs, 
<quantity box="[437,523,584,611]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.9" pageId="5" pageNumber="516" unit="mm" value="590.0">590 µm</quantity>
long (
<figureCitation box="[594,662,585,611]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1952,1977]" captionTargetBox="[162,1425,181,1926]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[162,1425,181,1926]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 8. A Rostrum (arrows) of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber; B duplicate image with overlaid dotted outline of rostrum and interpretation of segmentation adopted in description. Scale bar = 560 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3944005" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3944005/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="516">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). Anal opening with tube-like structure, probably constructed of wax, arising from anal ring at posterior apex of body, wax tube curved ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[1002,1071,621,647]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="8.[151,250,957,982]" captionTargetBox="[217,1370,181,931]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[217,1370,181,931]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 9. Posterior body portion of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber. A = Anal opening. O = ovisac with developing larvae. Scale bar = 685 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3944007" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3944007/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="516">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). Apparent waxy ovisac present, with evidence of immature forms within (
<figureCitation box="[616,693,657,683]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="8.[151,250,957,982]" captionTargetBox="[217,1370,181,931]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[217,1370,181,931]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 9. Posterior body portion of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber. A = Anal opening. O = ovisac with developing larvae. Scale bar = 685 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3944007" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3944007/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="516">Figs. 9</figureCitation>
and 
<figureCitation box="[746,777,657,683]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1978,2003]" captionTargetBox="[219,1367,1040,1953]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[219,1368,1040,1953]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 10. Section of ovisac of Paleolepidotus macrocolus gen. et sp. n. in Burmese amber showing outline of a larva (arrow). Scale bar = 140 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3944009" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3944009/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="516">10</figureCitation>
). Abdominal and thoracic spiracles and cuticular pores and ducts not discernible.
